T1  - Saving Incentives for Low- and Middle-Income Families: Evidence from a Field Experiment with H&amp;R Block
PY  - 2006
Y1  - 2006/11/01
DO  - 10.1093/qje/121.4.1311
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 121
IS  - 4
SP  - 1311
EP  - 1346
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - We analyze a randomized experiment in which 14,000 tax filers in H&amp;R Block offices in St. Louis received matches of zero, 20 percent, or 50 percent of IRA contributions. Take-up rates were 3 percent, 8 percent, and 14 percent, respectively. Among contributors, contributions, excluding the match, averaged $765 in the control group and $1100 in the match groups. Taxpayer responses to similar incentives in the Saver's Credit are much smaller. Taxpayers did not game the experiment by receiving a match and strategically withdrawing funds. Tax professionals significantly influenced contribution choices. These results suggest that both incentives and information affect behavior.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/qje/121.4.1311
ER  - 



